The paper deals with community structure in complex networks, which is a topic that falls under the umbrella of social network analysis and network science. The use of complex-valued eigenvectors and stochastic propagator eigenvalues suggests a focus on linear algebra and graph theory. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.SI (Social and Information Networks). However, the paper also deals with the extraction of communities with particular topological structure, which is a problem in graph theory and algorithms, suggesting that cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) are also likely sub-categories. The use of theoretic results and real-world examples suggests that cs.SD (Software Engineering) and cs.LG (Machine Learning) are also possible sub-categories.
